00:00:00.365 --> 00:00:02.610
- I get a lot of questions
about bone density.

00:00:02.610 --> 00:00:04.860
This is because my first invention,

00:00:04.860 --> 00:00:07.860
which can be found at
Osteostrong locations,

00:00:07.860 --> 00:00:10.800
is a medical device that puts axial.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:13.980
This is the axis of a
bone compression, so end

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:15.990
to end compression on bone.

00:00:15.990 --> 00:00:18.030
This stimulates the bone

00:00:18.030 --> 00:00:21.150
to deform slightly when the bone deforms.

00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:22.890
If you ever look at the inside of a bone

00:00:22.890 --> 00:00:24.150
or a picture of the inside of a bone,

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:26.220
it looks like a honeycomb.

00:00:26.220 --> 00:00:30.300
There are all sorts of little
walls, and as those walls bend

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:34.200
and become distorted, they're
stimulated to pull in minerals

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:37.260
and rec calcified, building
more little walls in

00:00:37.260 --> 00:00:39.720
between the nuclei of the cells,

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:41.970
increasing the density of bone.

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:45.180
There's a lot of myths in this space.

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:49.050
Many people say all you
need to do is exercise.

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:53.070
Well, here's the problem,
the minimum dose response

00:00:53.070 --> 00:00:54.840
for the hip joint, and

00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:58.620
that is the most important
place for bone density.

00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:00.870
We track spinal bone density

00:01:00.870 --> 00:01:02.820
and hip bone density, typically in,

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:05.640
in the health measurements of DEXA scans.

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:07.290
That's the sort of standard of care.

00:01:08.310 --> 00:01:12.600
When tracking those things,
the hip matters much more

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:17.580
because hip fractures are
associated with mortality.

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:22.470
So the statistic is you
have a 50% chance of death

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:28.110
within one year of a hip fracture

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:33.000
after the age of 50, 50%
chance after the age of 50.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.940
I know that sounds crazy.
Now, how do these people die?

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:37.230
They break their hip. That doesn't sound

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:38.760
like a life-threatening thing.

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.680
The problem is they
break their hip, they go

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:44.310
to the hospital, they can't recover

00:01:44.310 --> 00:01:47.820
because it needs a lot of body
resources to rebuild that.

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:49.320
And also some of the time,

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:51.840
the bone shatters
instead of a clean break.

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:55.410
And a lot, a lot of that has
to do with bisphosphate drugs.

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:58.290
There's a whole classification
of drugs that are supposed

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:00.000
to protect you from fragility fracture.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.570
But if you do have a fracture,
the fractures are real bad.

00:02:05.070 --> 00:02:08.940
When this happens, you can't heal

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:10.170
because there's too many pieces.

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:12.360
The doctors can't screw 'em all back in.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.120
Sometimes there's a mesh
that goes around the bone.

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:16.590
Keep in mind to do the surgery,

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:19.080
they gotta rip all the
muscle away from the bone

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:21.390
to get at it and to put
everything back in place.

00:02:22.230 --> 00:02:24.960
You really do not want
a fragility fracture.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:28.440
So how do you build bone density?

00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:32.850
Now, there are a number

00:02:32.850 --> 00:02:34.710
of osteostrong centers.

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:37.050
That's the ultimate,

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:40.500
because that's a machine
that uses robotic arms

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.140
to put you in exactly
the right position so

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:45.660
that you're just short of
lockout, 120 degree angle.

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:47.340
Same thing with the legs,
but it's easier for me

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:48.990
to demonstrate with my arm here.

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:52.770
So you are contracting in a
very small range of motion

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:55.050
to try and load these bones.

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:57.480
The radius, the oma,
the humerus, all the way

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:00.010
through the clavicle, the all
the extremities, that's one

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:03.550
of the four movements, gives
you incredible loading.

00:03:03.550 --> 00:03:07.510
Now, you don't have access to this.

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:10.510
There are a number of things you can do.

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:13.990
So if you're deconditioned, let's say you,

00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:15.130
you couldn't just get up

00:03:15.130 --> 00:03:17.860
and jog, you don't have
a coordination for that.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:20.080
You haven't been athletic in a long time.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:23.740
What I want you to do
is focus on heel drops.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:26.590
So what you do is you stand
on your toes and drop down,

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:30.670
and you're getting some level of loading.

00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:34.450
Now, every time I heel
hits, my whole body needs

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:35.710
to rebalance itself.

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:39.220
So my obliques are firing, my
quadratus muscles are firing,

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:41.560
my abs are firing, my
spinal erectus are firing.

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:45.580
All of these muscles are
firing to stabilize me,

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.780
and that's going to make me
better at more challenging

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:51.610
ways of loading body.

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:54.760
Like if I, instead of just
heel dropping, I actually want

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:59.560
to jump, I tow strike when I land,

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:01.240
as we all are supposed to.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:04.420
Now over time, you get, you build your way

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:06.640
to a plyometric jump.

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:08.650
So something more like this.

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:15.195
Now when you jump like that,
you can actually get to the,

00:04:15.195 --> 00:04:18.790
and this is the important
part, minimum dose response,

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:23.230
as in the minimum amount
of loading that's required

00:04:23.230 --> 00:04:25.570
to stimulate growth in the hip joint.

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:29.380
This is 4.2 multiples of body weight.

00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:33.130
So for those of you who are
still thinking, oh yeah, I'm,

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:34.180
I'm getting that in the gym,

